args: If I'm to live with my darling, I must learn\nall I can about human culture.
Right, then! Perhaps I'll begin\nby studying this handy magazine.
I've been reading about how humans\npair off during an event known as\na ＂wedding ceremony.＂
This must be the reason my darling still\nrefuses to acknowledge our love—\nwe haven't performed this ritual!
Wait, THAT'S your theory?! *sigh*\nWell, I suppose I can tell you\nwhat little I know of the subject.

Now then! A wedding ceremony is when
two partners stand before an audience
and take sacred vows to love one
another for all time.
How is that different from the pact my\ndarling and I swore to one another?
*ahem* You see, a wedding must take\nplace in a sacred location—and the\npair must walk down an aisle.
Then, in the presence of a priest, each\nmember of the pair must swear their\nundying love and fidelity to each other.

Oh, and inviting family and friends to
witness the ceremony and give their
blessing is an absolutely DELIGHTFUL
component of the whole affair.
Finally, at the end of the event, you toss\na bouquet of flowers into the air to share\nyour happiness with all!
Then the starry-eyed lovers board a\ncarriage and are whisked off on their\nromantic honeymoon. *siiiiigh*
Oh, just think of a wedding ceremony\nbetween me and my darling!
The following is a work of Mym's imagination.\nAny resemblance to actual persons or events\nis purely coincidental.
We're getting married!\nIt's like something out of a dream.
Ha ha! It is no dream, my snuggle-muffin.
From this day forth, we shall no longer\nbe you and I—instead, we shall be US!
Do you swear to love one another,\nin sickness and in health, so long as\nyou both shall live?
Then, beneath these hallowed eaves has\nbeen formed the greatest couple in the\nlong and storied history of Alberia!
I see why they call her the Flamewyrm,\n'cause she is SMOKIN'!
Oh, I am ever so happy to see my little\nangel all grown up and married to such\na wise and beautiful woman.
Why, I think I may like the bride\nbetter than my own child!
Stop! I object to this union! For it was\nI who had my sights set on being the\nbride of fair {player_name}!
Oh dear. We seem to lack a bouquet.\nI suppose we'll just have to use...THIS!
How lucky I am to have a wife who\nhurls my friends about the room!
You are such a rascal, my sweet.
Hee hee! Don't make me blush, dear.

Now come, my lovely! Let us board our
carriage—drawn by the noblest steeds
in the land—and be off on a honeymoon
that bards will sing of for ages to come!
Uh, guys? This is gettin' really weird.\nI mean, I'm just neighin'.
Bah! This lumpy old carriage will leave us\nwith naught but sore rears and sadness.\nI have a MUCH better ride in mind!
Now then, hop up and ride on MY back,\ndarling! It's so delightfully comfortable,\nyou'll swear you're surfing on a cloud!
But is it proper to have me astride you,\nO love of my life?
Pishposh! There's no need for such chastity\nnow that we are husband and wife!
Hee hee hee! Oooo, you devil...\nYou know my horns are ticklish...
...And furthermore, when the onlookers\ntoss their rice into the air, it should\nalways be of the long-grain variety.

Now then, when it comes to gift bags,
one can hardly go wrong with adorable
plush versions of the bride and groom.
However, other acceptable ideas include...
Those two have been whispering to each\nother for a very long time now.
